9:00 PM ET Open for Fellowship

💻 TECH HOST - While people are coming in
Open the Zoom application on your computer. Enter 5d.zoom.username@gmail.com as the username and the password (which the Volunteer Coordinator should have shared with you).
Click the “Meetings” tab (if you’re not already there). Click “Start” under “Welcome to 5D!”
As Tech Host, please rename yourself using the format: Tech Host, * [First Name] (pronouns), [location] — for example: Tech Host, * Bob (they/them), Akron, OH. Add an asterisk if you're available as a sponsor. Also, rename service volunteers to reflect their roles: #meeting chair – [Name], #time keeper – [Name], and #greeter – [Name]. This helps everyone know who’s doing what. You can assist if someone forgets how to rename.
Make the Meeting Chair a co-host.
Ask the Meeting Chair what the meeting format will be and make the following preparations:
For speaker discussion meetings: confirm with the Meeting Chair or speaker whether the speaker is ok being recorded.
(Mondays & Wednesdays are always speaker discussion meetings)
For Wednesdays: make sure you know who is providing ASL interpretation so you’re ready to spotlight and later pin their video.
If attendees have a phone number or email as their name, rename them to their first name if they mention it. Continue to do this throughout the meeting.

Every block like this is for the Tech Host, or for whomever is COPY/PASTING for the Tech Host, to paste into the chat.

Before the Meeting Starts

💻 TECH HOST - Ask for help!
The following is a suggested division of responsibilities so that the Meeting Chair can focus on reading the script, folks that need tech support receive it, and safety concerns are effectively addressed. Be sure to only make someone a co-host with their permission except in emergencies.
Ask at least 1 homegroup member if they are comfortable serving as co-host to scan through the attendees for Zoom-bombers and remove them. If possible, ask more experienced members so newer members can focus on the meeting.
Ask 1 homegroup member if they are comfortable serving as co-host to admit people from the waiting room.
If someone is definitely a Zoom-bomber based on their name, the co-host should alert you instead of admitting them. Temporarily turn off the ability for attendees to rename themselves, admit the person, and immediately remove them. Then you can turn back on the ability for attendees to rename themselves.
Ask 1 homegroup member if they are comfortable copying and pasting as directed by the script. Or if you are copying and pasting to have them share their screen for the reading (you can share, or meeting chair or another member).
Link to slides for the readings to screen share
Google Slides Link
5D Meeting Script Slides - Google Slides
 TECH HOST - Settings for the meeting
In the “Participants” window under “More,” uncheck “Allow Participants to Unmute Themselves” Then click “Mute All”.
In the “Chat” window, click ‘...’ and change the “Participant can chat with” setting to “Host and Co-Hosts.”
💻 TECH HOST - NAVIGATING ZOOM/HANDLING CHALLENGING SITUATIONS
How to Mute/Unmute All
Go to the participants menu and click “Mute All.” Make sure that in the options menu, you’ve un-clicked allowing participants to unmute themselves.
How to Lock/Unlock Chat
Go to the chat and click the drop-down that says “To: Everyone.” Change that to “To: No One or Host and Co-Hosts.”
Choppy Audio
If someone speaking is difficult to understand due to choppy audio, turn off their video and briefly explain why (in your own words, “so-and-so, I turned off your video to try to help with the connection because your audio is choppy”).
Bombers
If someone is obviously a bomber (a fake name), and is in the Waiting Room, click both “Participants” and “Chat” then click “More” and un-check allowing participants to change their names. Let the person into the meeting, and then immediately remove them.
**If someone has an offensive image or video, remove the person from the meeting.
Same thing if they are unmuted and share something offensive/off-topic, or if they post offensive content in the chat.
🧾 MEETING CHAIR INSTRUCTIONS
Reference: the 5D meeting chair job description is located at this link.
Reminder: Hop on by 9:15pm ET so we’ve got time to get things set up before we kick off.
Line up readers before the meeting (optional): If you want, tag a few folks to read the Quick Intro, 12 Steps, 12 Traditions, the Promises, and the sobriety milestones. Just make sure they know where to find the readings—either in the chat or on screen .
Day-specific stuff:
Sunday (Service): Choose a speaker or service-focused literature. If it’s a speaker please ask them to share on a service-related topic.
Monday (Speaker): Choose a speaker.
Tuesday (Big Book): Make sure someone’s ready to read the Big Book section. Check this link to see the Big Book Study Schedule. Remember to update the calendar with who you chose to read and what was read each night.
Wednesday (YPAA speaker): Check with the speaker if they’re cool with being recorded and if someone’s gonna introduce them.
Thursday (12 & 12): Check this link to see the 12 & 12 Study Schedule. Remember to update the calendar with who you chose to read and what was read each night.
Friday (Newcomers): Remember to focus on topics that are helpful for newcomers. You can choose from AA approved literature, Topic Speaker, or combined topic speaker and literature discussion.
Saturday (Meeting chair’s choice): Choose a speaker or literature. On the last Saturday of the month follow the Anniversary format. (How to share): You can mix things up… like “Tag”, “Pick a Number”, “Pull a Name out of a Hat”, or a “Topic Wheel” instead of just “raise hand.” Just keep it all rooted in AA principles and AA Conference-Approved Literature.
Service Calendar Updates : Suggestion is to update or ask someone to update the calendar with speaker names, readings, and/or meeting topics as far in advance as possible.
Burning desires (optional): If time permits, ask if anyone has a burning desire to share. Elsewise, invite those with burning desire to share after the meeting closes.
Two or more speakers (optional): In speaker meetings it’s cool to ask two or more speakers for shorter talks, but the total share time should remain the same.
Reminder: In literature readings, ensure the footnotes (asterisks) are read before moving on to the next page.
Lead with care: “We are not a glum lot”. It’s okay to speak from the heart or off the cuff—just be sure to follow the meeting script and stay grounded in AA principles.
Handling disruptions ("bombers"): Disruptors are seeking attention. Let co-hosts quietly remove them. An explanation to the meeting attendees is rarely needed unless inappropriate content was shared aloud or in the chat.
Open meetings reminder: As stated in our Quick Intro and from The A.A. Group pamphlet, 5D meetings are open meetings. "Open meetings are available to anyone interested in Alcoholics Anonymous' program of recovery from alcoholism. Nonalcoholics may attend open meetings as observers." We ask that only those who think they may have a problem with alcohol share in the meeting.

 TECH HOST: Safety Support [PASTE IN CHAT]
Copy
⚠️ SAFETY SUPPORT
If an incident occurs where you feel unsafe and you’d like support, let our Quick Response Committee know by filling out our safety form: https://bitly.com/5d-safety
For immediate support, please reach out to the Tech Host or Co-Host at any time.
 MEETING CHAIR: Our group insists on maintaining a safe and welcoming environment. Do not private message anyone you don’t know, during or after the meeting, unless it’s regarding recovery. Complimenting strangers on their appearance is unwelcome here, don’t do it. If someone is sending you inappropriate messages, you can let our Quick Response Committee know by filling out our safety form which is now in the chat. You can also message the Tech host or a Co-Host for immediate support. We encourage everyone to take any additional precautions you feel are necessary, such as turning off your camera or not using your full name. In addition, we ask everyone to respect one another’s anonymity. Please do not take screenshots or any recording of any kind, before, during, or after the meeting.
 TECH HOST: Quick Intro to A.A. & our group [PASTE IN CHAT]
Copy
QUICK INTRO TO A.A. & OUR GROUP Alcoholics Anonymous is a fellowship of people who share their experience, strength, and hope with each other so that they may solve their common problem and help others to recover from alcoholism. AA is not allied with any sect, denomination, politics, organization, or institution; does not wish to engage in any controversy; neither endorses nor opposes any causes. Our primary purpose is to stay sober and help other alcoholics to achieve sobriety. The Fifth Dimension Young People’s group has been meeting online since 2013. Our meetings are open, which means anyone is welcome to attend, even people who don’t identify as AA members or feel they are not young. “Young” can also mean “you still have room to grow.” Adapted from the A.A. preamble.
 MEETING CHAIR: I’ve asked to read a quick introduction to AA and our group.
 TECH HOST: The 7th Tradition Statement [PASTE IN CHAT — After quick introduction is read]
Copy
Our 7th Tradition states: "Every A.A. group ought to be fully self-supporting, declining outside contributions." As members, we contribute what we can to help keep the group going. There are no dues or fees for A.A. membership. Important: Be sure to enter "5d" in the note or memo section when prompted. This ensures your contribution reaches our group. If you have any questions, please contact our Treasurer at: 5d.contributions@gmail.com Thank you for supporting the group. Please only contribute if you identify as a member of A.A. https://donate.homegroup.online/5d/

 MEETING CHAIR:  In keeping with A.A.’s 7th Tradition statement which states that every A.A. group ought to be fully self-supporting, declining outside contributions — we only accept contributions from A.A. members. If you need help, feel free to message the Tech Host or a co-host.
 TECH HOST: Twelve Steps [PASTE IN CHAT — After 7th tradition is read]
Copy
THE TWELVE STEPS 1. We admitted we were powerless over alcohol—that our lives had become unmanageable. 2. Came to believe that a Power greater than ourselves could restore us to sanity. 3. Made a decision to turn our will and our lives over to the care of God as we understood Him. 4. Made a searching and fearless moral inventory of ourselves. 5. Admitted to God, to ourselves, and to another human being the exact nature of our wrongs. 6. Were entirely ready to have God remove all these defects of character.
Copy
THE TWELVE STEPS CONT.. 7. Humbly asked Him to remove our shortcomings. 8. Made a list of all persons we had harmed and became willing to make amends to them all. 9. Made direct amends to such people wherever possible, except when to do so would injure them or others. 10. Continued to take personal inventory and when we were wrong promptly admitted it. 11. Sought through prayer and meditation to improve our conscious contact with God as we understood Him, praying only for knowledge of His will for us and the power to carry that out. 12. Having had a spiritual awakening as the result of these steps, we tried to carry this message to alcoholics and to practice these principles in all our affairs.
 MEETING CHAIR: I’ve now asked to read the Twelve Steps.
 TECH HOST: Twelve Traditions [PASTE IN CHAT — After 12 Steps are read]
Copy
THE TWELVE TRADITIONS 1. Our common welfare should come first; personal recovery depends upon A.A.unity. 2. For our group purpose there is but one ultimate authority—a loving God as He may express Himself in our group conscience. Our leaders are but trusted servants; they do not govern. 3. The only requirement for A.A. membership is a desire to stop drinking. 4. Each group should be autonomous except in matters affecting other groups or A.A. as a whole. 5. Each group has but one primary purpose—to carry its message to the alcoholic who still suffers. 6. An A.A. group ought never endorse, finance, or lend the A.A. name to any related facility or outside enterprise, lest problems of money, property, and prestige divert us from our primary purpose.
Copy
THE TWELVE TRADITIONS CONT… 7. Every A.A. group ought to be fully self-supporting, declining outside contributions. 8. Alcoholics Anonymous should remain forever nonprofessional, but our service centers may employ special workers. 9. A.A., as such, ought never be organized; but we may create service boards or committees directly responsible to those they serve. 10. Alcoholics Anonymous has no opinion on outside issues; hence the A.A. name ought never be drawn into public controversy. 11. Our public relations policy is based on attraction rather than promotion; we need always maintain personal anonymity at the level of press, radio, and films. 12. Anonymity is the spiritual foundation of all our Traditions, ever reminding us to place principles before personalities.
 MEETING CHAIR: I’ve asked to read the Twelve Traditions.
 TECH HOST: THE 9th STEP PROMISES [PASTE IN CHAT — After 12 Traditions are read]
Copy
THE 9th STEP PROMISES “If we are painstaking about this phase of our development, we will be amazed before we are half way through. We are going to know a new freedom and a new happiness. We will not regret the past nor wish to shut the door on it. We will comprehend the word serenity and we will know peace. No matter how far down the scale we have gone, we will see how our experience can benefit others. That feeling of uselessness and self-pity will disappear. We will lose interest in selfish things and gain interest in our fellows. Self-seeking will slip away. Our whole attitude and outlook upon life will change.
Copy
Fear of people and of economic insecurity will leave us. We will intuitively know how to handle situations which used to baffle us. We will suddenly realize that God is doing for us what we could not do for ourselves. Are these extravagant promises? We think not. They are being fulfilled among us—sometimes quickly, sometimes slowly. They will always materialize if we work for them.” Pg 83-84, Alcoholics Anonymous https://www.aa.org/sites/default/files/2021-11/en_bigbook_chapt6.pdf

Anniversary Format [Use on last Saturday of each month]
